---
---
<section class="mb-12">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6 text-text-primary">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  
  <div class="space-y-4">
    <details class="group bg-surface border border-border-subtle rounded-lg open:bg-base transition-colors" open>
      <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer p-4 font-medium text-text-primary">
        Is my data safe? Does the converter send data to a server?
        <span class="transition group-open:rotate-180">
          <svg fill="none" height="24" shape-rendering="geometricPrecision" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"></path></svg>
        </span>
      </summary>
      <div class="p-4 pt-0 text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        No. This converter runs entirely in your browser using client-side JavaScript. Your data never leaves your device — nothing is uploaded, stored, or transmitted.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="group bg-surface border border-border-subtle rounded-lg open:bg-base transition-colors">
      <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer p-4 font-medium text-text-primary">
        What is the maximum file size I can convert?
        <span class="transition group-open:rotate-180">
          <svg fill="none" height="24" shape-rendering="geometricPrecision" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"></path></svg>
        </span>
      </summary>
      <div class="p-4 pt-0 text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        There is no hard limit, but for optimal performance we recommend files under 50 MB. Larger files are processed efficiently, but very large datasets may temporarily slow down your browser.
      </div>
    </details>

    <details class="group bg-surface border border-border-subtle rounded-lg open:bg-base transition-colors">
      <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer p-4 font-medium text-text-primary">
        Can I convert nested JSON objects?
        <span class="transition group-open:rotate-180">
          <svg fill="none" height="24" shape-rendering="geometricPrecision" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"></path></svg>
        </span>
      </summary>
      <div class="p-4 pt-0 text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Yes. The converter automatically detects nested structures and flattens them using dot-notation (e.g., <code class="text-sm bg-surface px-1 py-0.5 rounded">user.address.city</code> becomes a column).
      </div>
    </details>
    
    <details class="group bg-surface border border-border-subtle rounded-lg open:bg-base transition-colors">
      <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer p-4 font-medium text-text-primary">
        Does it work with JSON arrays of different structures?
        <span class="transition group-open:rotate-180">
          <svg fill="none" height="24" shape-rendering="geometricPrecision" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"></path></svg>
        </span>
      </summary>
      <div class="p-4 pt-0 text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Yes. The schema detector analyzes all objects in the array and creates a superset of all unique keys. Objects missing a key will have an empty value in that column.
      </div>
    </details>
    
    <details class="group bg-surface border border-border-subtle rounded-lg open:bg-base transition-colors">
      <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer p-4 font-medium text-text-primary">
        Can I use a custom delimiter instead of commas?
        <span class="transition group-open:rotate-180">
          <svg fill="none" height="24" shape-rendering="geometricPrecision" stroke="currentColor" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="24"><path d="M6 9l6 6 6-6"></path></svg>
        </span>
      </summary>
      <div class="p-4 pt-0 text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Yes. You can choose between comma (,), tab, or semicolon (;) as your delimiter in the options bar.
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is my data safe? Does the converter send data to a server?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "No. This converter runs entirely in your browser using client-side JavaScript. Your data never leaves your device — nothing is uploaded, stored, or transmitted." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the maximum file size I can convert?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "There is no hard limit, but for optimal performance we recommend files under 50 MB. Larger files are processed efficiently, but very large datasets may temporarily slow down your browser." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can I convert nested JSON objects?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. The converter automatically detects nested structures and flattens them using dot-notation (e.g., user.address.city becomes a column)." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Does it work with JSON arrays of different structures?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. The schema detector analyzes all objects in the array and creates a superset of all unique keys. Objects missing a key will have an empty value in that column." }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can I use a custom delimiter instead of commas?",
          "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Yes. You can choose between comma (,), tab, or semicolon (;) as your delimiter in the options bar." }
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>
</section>
